        <h2 id="best-practices">Social media dashboard best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Only track metrics you act on.</strong> A dashboard with 40 metrics and no clear decision-making framework is as bad as no dashboard at all. Start with 5-8 core KPIs and add others only when there's a reason to track them.</li>
          <li><strong>Set benchmarks before you start.</strong> Record your baseline metrics when you first set up the dashboard. Without a baseline, you can't evaluate whether changes you make are working.</li>
          <li><strong>Use the same date range for comparisons.</strong> Always compare like for like: same-period last year, or previous equivalent period. Comparing a 31-day month to a 28-day month without adjusting will produce misleading trends.</li>
          <li><strong>Build separate views for different audiences.</strong> The social media manager needs granular post-level data. The CMO needs 5 headline numbers. Build separate dashboard views rather than one all-inclusive screen.</li>
          <li><strong>Review and refresh the dashboard quarterly.</strong> Platforms change their APIs, new platforms emerge, and your KPIs may shift with business goals. A quarterly review keeps the dashboard aligned with current reality.</li>
          <li><strong>Combine social data with business data.</strong> The most powerful dashboards connect social metrics to downstream business outcomes: website sessions from social, leads attributed to social, revenue influenced by social. This requires pulling in data from Google Analytics or a CRM alongside social platform data.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Don't confuse dashboard activity with analysis</div>
          <p>Checking the dashboard every morning is monitoring. Analysing why engagement rate has declined three weeks in a row, forming a hypothesis, testing a change, and measuring the result is analysis. Dashboards support analysis — they don't replace it. If your team's social media practice is all dashboard-checking and no experimentation, you're collecting data without using it.</p>
        </div>

